      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Plans have been proposed to harvest Brazil's Amazonian rain forest, and predictions are that it could be done in just a few decades. No one could blame Brazil for exploiting its greatest natural resource to enliven its economy. Yet I wonder if this country, or the Soviet Union, can allow this to happen.</p>
        <p>As the vastest tract of its kind, the Amazon basin is the earth's eminent producer of oxygen, and the recently noticed rents in the Antarctic ozone layer suggest that this commodity might be in shorter supply than we have realized.</p>
        <p>The day is probably coming when ''developed'' countries such as the United States and the Soviet Union will have to offer ''undeveloped'' countries around the equatorial belt considerable financial inducements to leave their topographies much as they charmingly are now. That is going to mean cooperation in the strictest sense. RALPH HODGES  Hoboken, N.J., Oct. 8, 1987</p>
      </block>
